ncode-install-guide-step-by-step-2026)\n\n## Key Takeaways\n\n*   **Multiple install paths**: npm, Homebrew, curl script, Go install, Docker, and building from source -- pick whichever fits your toolchain.\n*   **Five minutes to first run**: The fastest path (curl install script) gets OpenCode running in under five minutes on any Unix system.\n*   **Provider-agnostic**: OpenCode works with OpenAI, Google Gemini, Ollama local models, and more -- you are not locked into a single AI provider.\n*   **Configuration is minimal**: A single `config.toml` file and one environment variable are all you need to start coding with AI in your terminal.\n\n# How to Install OpenCode: Step-by-Step Setup Guide (2026)\n\nOpenCode is the open-source AI coding agent built for the terminal. It brings the power of large language models directly into your command line, letting you write, refactor, debug, and understand code without leaving your editor or terminal workflow.\n\nWhether you are setting up OpenCode for the first time or migrating from another AI coding tool, this guide walks you through every installation method, initial configuration, provider setup, and troubleshooting step you will need.\n\n* * *\n\n## Prerequisites\n\nBefore installing OpenCode, confirm your system meets the following requirements.\n\n**Operating System**\n\nOpenCode runs on macOS, Linux, and Windows. For Windows users, WSL (Windows Subsystem for Linux) is strongly recommended. Native Windows support via Scoop is also available.\n\n**Runtime Requirements (depends on install method)**\n\n| Install Method | Requirement |\n| --- | --- |\n| npm | Node.js 18 or higher |\n| Homebrew | macOS or Linux with Homebrew installed |\n| Curl script | bash, curl |\n| Go install | Go 1.22 or higher |\n| Docker | Docker Engine 20+ |\n| Build from source | Go 1.22+, Git |\n\n**Terminal Requirements**\n\nOpenCode provides a TUI (Terminal User Interface), so your terminal emulator must support true color and proper Unicode rendering. Most modern terminals (iTerm2, Alacritty, WezTerm, Windows Terminal, Ghostty) work out of the box. Older terminals like the default macOS Terminal.app may have rendering issues.\n\nCheck your Node.js version:\n\n```bash\nnode --version\n```\n\nCheck your Go version (if using the Go install method):\n\n```bash\ngo version\n```\n\n* * *\n\n### Describe what you want — NxCode builds it for you.\n\nTurn your idea into a working app — no coding required.\n\nStart Free\n\n## Method 1: Install Script (Fastest)\n\nThe official install script is the quickest way to get OpenCode running. It detects your OS and architecture, downloads the correct binary, and places it in your PATH.\n\n```bash\ncurl -fsSL https://opencode.ai/install | bash\n```\n\nThis single command handles everything. After it completes, verify the installation:\n\n```bash\nopencode --version\n```\n\nThis method works on macOS and Linux. It does not require Node.js or Go.\n\n* * *\n\n## Method 2: npm Install\n\nIf you already have Node.js in your workflow, npm is the most familiar option.\n\n```bash\nnpm install -g opencode-ai@latest\n```\n\nThe package name on npm is `opencode-ai`, not `opencode`. This is a common source of confusion.\n\nTo verify:\n\n```bash\nopencode --version\n```\n\nIf you encounter permission errors, either fix your npm global directory permissions or use npx to run it without a global install:\n\n```bash\nnpx opencode-ai@latest\n```\n\n* * *\n\n## Method 3: Homebrew (macOS and Linux)\n\nHomebrew users can install OpenCode from the official tap:\n\n```bash\nbrew install anomalyco/tap/opencode\n```\n\nThis installs the latest stable release and handles updates through `brew upgrade`.\n\nTo verify:\n\n```bash\nopencode --version\n```\n\n* * *\n\n## Method 4: Go Install\n\nIf you have Go 1.22+ installed, you can install directly from source via `go install`:\n\n```bash\ngo install github.com/opencode-ai/opencode@latest\n```\n\nMake sure `$GOPATH/bin` (or `$HOME/go/bin` by default) is in your PATH. Add it to your shell profile if it is not already:\n\n```bash\nexport PATH=\"$PATH:$(go env GOPATH)/bin\"\n```\n\nVerify:\n\n```bash\nopencode --version\n```\n\n* * *\n\n## Method 5: Docker\n\nRunning OpenCode in Docker is useful for CI/CD pipelines or when you want an isolated environment.\n\n```bash\ndocker pull ghcr.io/opencode-ai/opencode:latest\n```\n\nRun it with your project directory mounted:\n\n```bash\ndocker run -it --rm \\\n  -v \"$(pwd)\":/workspace \\\n  -w /workspace \\\n  -e OPENAI_API_KEY=\"$OPENAI_API_KEY\" \\\n  ghcr.io/opencode-ai/opencode:latest\n```\n\nThe `-it` flags are essential because OpenCode uses an interactive TUI. The `-v` flag mounts your current project directory so OpenCode can read and modify your files.\n\n* * *\n\n## Method 6: Build from Source\n\nFor contributors or anyone who wants the bleeding-edge version:\n\n```bash\ngit clone https://github.com/opencode-ai/opencode.git\ncd opencode\ngo build -o opencode .\n```\n\nMove the binary to a directory in your PATH:\n\n```bash\nsudo mv opencode /usr/local/bin/\n```\n\nBuilding from source requires Go 1.22+ and Git. This gives you access to unreleased features and lets you modify the tool for your own needs.\n\n* * *\n\n## Method 7: Scoop (Windows)\n\nWindows users who prefer a native experience over WSL can use Scoop:\n\n```bash\nscoop install opencode\n```\n\nScoop handles PATH configuration automatically.\n\n* * *\n\n## First Launch and Configuration\n\nWith OpenCode installed, navigate to any project directory and launch it:\n\n```bash\ncd your-project\nopencode\n```\n\nOn first launch, OpenCode opens its TUI and prompts you to connect an AI provider. You can use the interactive `/connect` command to add your API key:\n\n```\n/connect\n```\n\nThis walks you through selecting a provider (OpenAI, Google, Anthropic, etc.) and entering your API key. Credentials are stored in `~/.local/share/opencode/auth.json`.\n\nFor a faster start, you can also initialize your project with:\n\n```\n/init\n```\n\nThis analyzes your repository structure and creates an `agents.md` file with context about your codebase, helping the AI give more accurate responses from the start.\n\n* * *\n\n## Configure AI Providers\n\nOpenCode supports multiple AI providers. Here is how to configure each one.\n\n**OpenAI (GPT-5.4, GPT-4.1, o3)**\n\nSet the API key as an environment variable:\n\n```bash\nexport OPENAI_API_KEY=\"sk-your-key-here\"\n```\n\nOr add it to your shell profile (`~/.zshrc`, `~/.bashrc`) for persistence.\n\n**Google Gemini (Gemini 2.5 Pro, Gemini 2.5 Flash)**\n\n```bash\nexport GOOGLE_API_KEY=\"your-google-api-key\"\n```\n\nYou can obtain a Google API key from [Google AI Studio](https://aistudio.google.com/).\n\n**Ollama (Local Models -- Free, Private)**\n\nOllama lets you run models locally without any API key. Install Ollama first, pull a model, then configure OpenCode:\n\n```bash\n# Install Ollama (if not already installed)\ncurl -fsSL https://ollama.com/install.sh | sh\n\n# Pull a coding model\nollama pull qwen2.5-coder:32b\n\n# OpenCode detects Ollama automatically when running on localhost:11434\n```\n\nNo API key is needed for Ollama. OpenCode auto-detects it when running locally.\n\n**Anthropic (Claude -- Limited Access)**\n\nAnthropic has restricted Claude access in third-party tools including OpenCode. If you have an API key that still works:\n\n```bash\nexport ANTHROPIC_API_KEY=\"sk-ant-your-key-here\"\n```\n\nHowever, most users in 2026 are using OpenAI or Gemini as their primary provider with OpenCode due to these restrictions.\n\n* * *\n\n## Essential Configuration: config.toml Walkthrough\n\nOpenCode uses a TOML configuration file for fine-grained control. The config file lives at `~/.config/opencode/config.toml` (or in your project root as `opencode.json` for project-specific settings).\n\nHere is a practical example of a `config.toml`:\n\n```toml\n# Provider configuration\n[provider.openai]\napiKey = \"{env:OPENAI_API_KEY}\"\n\n[provider.openai.models.gpt]\nid = \"gpt-5.4\"\n\n[provider.google]\napiKey = \"{env:GOOGLE_API_KEY}\"\n\n[provider.google.models.gemini]\nid = \"gemini-2.5-pro\"\n\n# Disable providers you do not use\ndisabled_providers = [\"anthropic\"]\n```\n\nKey things to note:\n\n*   **Variable substitution**: Use `{env:VARIABLE_NAME}` to reference environment variables instead of hardcoding keys.\n*   **Model selection**: You can specify exactly which model to use under each provider.\n*   **Disabled providers**: Prevent OpenCode from loading providers whose credentials you do not have, avoiding startup warnings.\n*   **Base URL override**: If you use a proxy or custom endpoint, add `baseURL = \"https://your-proxy.com/v1\"` under the provider section.\n\nFor project-level configuration, create an `opencode.json` in your project root:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"provider\": \"openai\",\n  \"model\": \"gpt-5.4\"\n}\n```\n\nThis overrides global settings for that specific project.\n\n* * *\n\n## Verify Your Installation\n\nRun through this checklist to confirm everything works correctly.\n\n**1. Check the version**\n\n```bash\nopencode --version\n```\n\nYou should see the version number printed. As of March 2026, the latest stable version is in the 0.x range.\n\n**2. Launch the TUI**\n\n```bash\ncd any-project-directory\nopencode\n```\n\nYou should see the OpenCode terminal interface with a prompt at the bottom.\n\n**3. Test a simple prompt**\n\nIn the OpenCode TUI, type a simple request:\n\n```\nExplain what this project does based on the file structure.\n```\n\nIf you get a response from the AI, your provider configuration is working.\n\n**4. Test file operations**\n\nAsk OpenCode to create a small test file:\n\n```\nCreate a file called test-opencode.txt with the text \"OpenCode is working\"\n```\n\nCheck that the file was created in your project directory, then delete it.\n\n* * *\n\n## Troubleshooting Common Issues\n\n**\"command not found: opencode\"**\n\nThe binary is not in your PATH. Solutions depend on your install method:\n\n*   npm: Run `npm list -g opencode-ai` to confirm installation. If installed, check that npm's global bin directory is in your PATH: `npm config get prefix` and add `/bin` to that path.\n*   Go: Add `$(go env GOPATH)/bin` to your PATH.\n*   Curl script: Re-run the install script or manually move the binary to `/usr/local/bin/`.\n\n**Permission errors during npm install**\n\nDo not use `sudo npm install -g`. Instead, fix npm's default directory:\n\n```bash\nmkdir -p ~/.npm-global\nnpm config set prefix '~/.npm-global'\necho 'export PATH=\"$HOME/.npm-global/bin:$PATH\"' >> ~/.zshrc\nsource ~/.zshrc\nnpm install -g opencode-ai@latest\n```\n\n**\"Error: Node.js version too old\"**\n\nOpenCode's npm package requires Node.js 18+. Check your version:\n\n```bash\nnode --version\n```\n\nIf you are on an older version, upgrade using nvm:\n\n```bash\nnvm install 18\nnvm use 18\n```\n\n**Network errors behind a corporate firewall**\n\nIf npm install hangs or fails due to network restrictions:\n\n```bash\nnpm install -g opencode-ai@latest --registry https://registry.npmmirror.com\n```\n\nOr download the binary directly from the [GitHub releases page](https://github.com/opencode-ai/opencode/releases) and place it in your PATH manually.\n\n**\"API key not found\" or \"No provider configured\"**\n\nMake sure your API key environment variable is exported in the same shell session:\n\n```bash\necho $OPENAI_API_KEY\n```\n\nIf it prints nothing, set it again:\n\n```bash\nexport OPENAI_API_KEY=\"sk-your-key-here\"\n```\n\nFor persistence, add the export line to your `~/.zshrc` or `~/.bashrc` and run `source ~/.zshrc`.\n\n**TUI rendering issues (garbled text, missing borders)**\n\nSwitch to a modern terminal emulator that supports true color. Recommended options: iTerm2 (macOS), Alacritty (cross-platform), WezTerm (cross-platform), or Windows Terminal (Windows).\n\n**Go install: \"go: command not found\"**\n\nGo is not installed or not in your PATH. Install Go from [go.dev/dl](https://go.dev/dl/) and ensure it is in your PATH:\n\n```bash\nexport PATH=\"$PATH:/usr/local/go/bin\"\n```\n\n* * *\n\n## Updating OpenCode\n\nKeep OpenCode current to get the latest model support and bug fixes.\n\n**npm**:\n\n```bash\nnpm update -g opencode-ai\n```\n\n**Homebrew**:\n\n```bash\nbrew upgrade opencode\n```\n\n**Curl script**: Re-run the install command:\n\n```bash\ncurl -fsSL https://opencode.ai/install | bash\n```\n\n**Go install**: Re-run with `@latest`:\n\n```bash\ngo install github.com/opencode-ai/opencode@latest\n```\n\n* * *\n\n## Next Steps\n\nNow that OpenCode is installed and configured, you are ready to start using it in your daily workflow.\n\n*   **Learn the commands**: Check out our [OpenCode Tutorial 2026](https://www.nxcode.io/resources/news/opencode-tutorial-2026) for a full walkthrough of commands, workflows, and advanced features.\n*   **Set up GitHub integration**: Install the OpenCode GitHub App to use AI-powered code review and issue responses directly in your repositories.\n*   **Explore the `/init` command**: Run `/init` in your project to generate an `agents.md` file that gives OpenCode deep context about your codebase architecture.\n*   **Try multiple providers**: Configure two or three providers and switch between them to find which model works best for your coding tasks.\n\nOpenCode is one of the fastest-growing open-source AI tools in 2026 because it meets developers where they already work: the terminal. With installation taking under five minutes and configuration requiring just one API key, there is no reason not to try it today.\n\n[Back to all news](https://www.nxcode.io/resources/news)\n\nEnjoyed this article?Share it\n\n## Build with NxCode\n\nTurn your idea into a working app — no coding required.\n\nStart Free See Examples\n\n46,000+ developers built with NxCode this month\n\n## Now try it yourself\n\nDescribe what you want — NxCode builds it for you.\n\nBuild It Free →